To return to the start of the while loop, you can use the `continue` statement. The `continue` statement is used to immediately stop the current iteration of a loop and move on to the next iteration of the loop.

Here is an example of how you can use the `continue` statement to return to the start of a while loop:

```
bool done = false;

while (!done) {
    // do something

    if (some_condition_is_met) {
        // return to the start of the loop
        continue;
    }

    // do something else
}
```

In this example, the code inside the while loop will continue executing until `some_condition_is_met` evaluates to true. At that point, the `continue` statement is executed, which causes the program to immediately return to the start of the while loop and re-evaluate the condition. If the condition is still false, the loop will continue normally. If the condition is true, the code inside the if statement will be executed, and so on.

